TERA Algorithm — Time-Stability Coupling Logic

Overview

The TERA algorithm describes a stabilization mechanism for open systems in which information, energy, and temporal resonance interact to regulate state evolution.

Unlike purely deterministic control models, TERA assumes that real systems are non-hermetic:
they constantly exchange signals, disturbances, and information with their environment.

To maintain stability under these conditions, TERA introduces a time-stability coupling logic that continuously compares perception and model states and regulates their difference through a discrete decision gate.

---

Core Idea

A system maintains stability by minimizing the drift between two coupled spaces:

- Perception Space — what the system observes
- Model Space — what the system expects

The difference between them defines the information error space.

[
A(t) = \text{Perception Space}
]

[
B(t) = \text{Model Space}
]

[
C(t) = B(t) - A(t)
]

The objective of TERA is to keep

[
||C(t)|| \rightarrow \text{minimal}
]

over time.

---

State Representation

The system state evolves as

[
S(t)
]

with discrete updates

[
