]

State transitions are controlled by the interaction of three fundamental quantities:

- Information I
- Energy E
- Temporal Resonance \omega

---

Stability Measure

System stability is evaluated through a Lyapunov-like function

[
V(t) = ||C(t)||^2
]

The system is stable if

[
\Delta V(t) \le 0
]

which means the difference between perception and model does not increase.

---

Decision Gate

TERA regulates state transitions using a discrete gate.

ACCEPT
WAIT
REJECT

Decision rule:

ACCEPT  if s(p) < ε
WAIT    if ds/dt ≈ 0
REJECT  if s(p) ≥ ε

Where:

- s(p) represents system stress or instability
- ε is a stability threshold

---

TERA Master Relation

State changes are determined by a gated interaction of information, energy and resonance:

[
\Delta S = Gate(I \cdot E \cdot \omega)
]

This relation expresses that system evolution occurs only when the interaction between these quantities passes the stability gate.

---

Algorithm Structure

The algorithm operates as a continuous feedback loop.

Step 1 — Observe

Measure system perception state:

[
A(t)
]

Step 2 — Predict

Generate model state:

[
B(t)
]

Step 3 — Compute Drift

[
C(t) = B(t) - A(t)
]

Evaluate system stress:

[
s(p) = ||C(t)||
]

---

Step 4 — Gate Decision

if s(p) < ε:
    ACCEPT
elif |ds/dt| ≈ 0:
    WAIT
else:
    REJECT

---

Step 5 — Update State

Apply gated correction:

[
S(t+1) = S(t) + Gate(I,E,\omega)
]

